oss the Taiwan Strait after 1987 -- t14. Salvation and Rights in Hong Kong -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThis book explores the interaction between religion and nationalism in the Chinese societies of mainland China, Taiwan, and Hong Kong. Cheng-tian Kuo analyses the dominant religions, including Chinese Buddhism, Tibetan Buddhism, Daoism, Christianity, Islam, and folk religions, but he also goes beyond that, showing how in recent decades the Chinese state has tightened its control over religion to an unprecedented degree. Indeed, it could almost be said to have constructed a wholly new religion, Chinese Patriotism. The same period, however, has seen the growth of democratic civil religions, which could challenge the state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 0aNationalismxReligious aspects. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh1 aChau, Adam Yuet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTerrone, Antonio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDessein, Bart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuo, Cheng-tian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChang, Chi-shen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLin, Ching-chih, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrettingham, Edmund, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChang, Hsun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchneider, Julia C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 